p17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 24<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(3/31/02 4:32:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=499.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://home.earthlink.net/~projectorion/ezboard/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: What is your stance on nuclear power in space?</span><hr size=1> I think the results of mine show something valuable. Even the informed public, namely this board, do not want a nuclear rocket launched from the ground. NEP's are too slow for a ground launch, they don't have 1 g of thrust, and NTR would spew quite a bit of radioactivity around. So most people support nuclear rockets who are informed, so long as they aren't launched from the earth. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ustifled.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stifled</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 9:20:11 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=499.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What is your stance on nuclear power in space?</span><hr size=1> I would consider an NTR (using fresh fuel going critical only in high Earth orbit - the same standard that NASA uses) as being safer then an RTG. I voted for the orbital NTR, but I don't include the RTG as an automatic given. <br>
(Just trying to be scrupulous)<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ubrp17.showPublicProfile?language=EN>brp17</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 76<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/14/02 10:55:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=499.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What is your stance on nuclear power in space?</span><hr size=1> Most current nuclear propulsion systems, esp. those not starting from earth, use RTG's instead of more standard on earth methods. There are a few exceptions, VASMIR for one, Orion of course, but I think those are the only two. I may have misplaced a few of them, but most systems, including the most likely senario of a nuclear ion drive all use RTG's for their power source. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/ustifled.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Stifled</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Tourist</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(7/15/02 12:07:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=499.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: What is your stance on nuclear power in space?</span><hr size=1> Yes, most small power systems - low or fractional kilowatt outputs use RTGs. <br>
<br>
They are less safe within the biosphere than an equivalent output reactor that has never gone critical.<br>
<br>
Once in space, however the positions reverse, and the reactor is more problematical in the event of re-entry.<br>
<br>
My bottom line point is that I think the poll should not automatically include all technologies &quot;less then&quot; the choice.<br>
<br>
I assume I am still being obscure. Writing is not my forte.<br>
<br>
